  <!-- FLOWER CARE TIPS -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">✂️ Bloom & Care Tips</div>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(200px,1fr));gap:12px;">
      <div style="background:rgba(220,80,80,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(220,80,80,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#f5a0a0;margin-bottom:6px;">🌺 Zinnias</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Deadhead spent blooms regularly — this is the #1 trick for more flowers all season. Pinch off faded flowers to the next leaf node. The more you cut, the more they bloom. Cut for vases freely!
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(230,180,100,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(230,180,100,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#f5d97a;margin-bottom:6px;">🌸 Cosmos</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Also benefits from deadheading. Can be cut back by ⅓ mid-season if they get leggy (which they will in shade). Self-seeds freely — let a few go to seed at end of season for next year.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(155,127,196,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(155,127,196,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#c9a8f0;margin-bottom:6px;">💜 Columbine</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Native to Colorado — very low maintenance. Blooms spring/early summer then dies back. Let seed pods form and shake them around the bed to self-sow for next year. Don't deadhead if you want more plants.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(100,160,80,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(100,160,80,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#a8c89a;margin-bottom:6px;">🌱 Wildflower Mix</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Thin seedlings once 2–3" tall to avoid overcrowding. Most wildflowers need no fertilizer once established — they're adapted to lean soil. Don't over-tend; wildflowers thrive on neglect.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(100,180,180,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(100,180,180,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#90d4d4;margin-bottom:6px;">🌀 Fan Flowers (Scaevola)</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Self-cleaning — no deadheading needed at all. Pinch back leggy stems mid-summer to keep bushy. Very heat tolerant. Feed monthly with Miracle-Gro at half strength; they don't need heavy feeding.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(100,120,200,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(100,120,200,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#a0b0f0;margin-bottom:6px;">🪻 Periwinkle / Vinca</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Also self-cleaning. Hanging baskets dry out fast — check daily in Longmont heat even if you water every 2 days. Trim back by ⅓ mid-summer if trailing gets stringy. Monthly Miracle-Gro feeding keeps blooms coming.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(200,80,100,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(200,80,100,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#f0a0b0;margin-bottom:6px;">🌹 Rose Bush (budding)</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Deadhead every spent bloom by cutting to a 5-leaflet leaf node — this is what keeps roses blooming all season. Never water overhead. Watch for aphids (blast with hose) and black spot (remove affected leaves). Roses reward attention.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(200,80,100,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(200,80,100,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#f0a0b0;margin-bottom:6px;">🌹 Rose Pendulina (blooming)</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Alpine/wild rose — tougher than hybrid roses, more drought tolerant, less disease prone. Already blooming so skip to bloom fertilizer now. Produces attractive rosehips in fall — leave some blooms to go to seed for wildlife and visual interest.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:rgba(220,140,180,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(220,140,180,0.3);border-radius:8px;padding:12px;">
        <div style="font-weight:700;color:#e8b0d0;margin-bottom:6px;">🌺 Rose of Sharon</div>
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem;line-height:1.5;color:var(--petal);">
          Just greening up = vegetative stage, feed now with balanced fertilizer. Very low maintenance once established — drought tolerant, pest resistant. Blooms on new wood so a light spring prune encourages more flowers. Self-seeds prolifically; remove seed pods after bloom if you don't want dozens of seedlings next year.
        </div>
      </div>
